Species overview

Pinocchio’s dolphin (Delfinus mendax) is a long-lived odontocete found in several large, isolated, genetically-distinct coastal populations. It is easily identified by its often-elongated rostrum. It is largely solitary with no sexual dimorphism. It has one large tooth, retained through life; four milk-teeth at birth, one lost annually until maturity at age 5 (both sexes); females have one calf per year thereafter.

Pinocchio’s Dolphin gets taken as bycatch throughout its range, in gillnets and sometimes in other gears. There appears to be strong selectivity towards younger animals (based on age distribution of bycatch, vs. of apparently-natural strandings). Gear-naivety is one possible explanation, but another is that a longer rostrum is actually protective, since it gives the animal more warning before the fins (the part most vulnerable to entanglement) encounters the gillnet.

Heavy bycatch led to severe population reductions a couple of decades ago. Gear modifications have since reduced the rate, and there is a suggestion that some recovery may be taking place. In several populations, scientists/managers had the foresight to start genetic-sampling of bycatch a few years ago, so that CKMR is now a good option.

The population we are focusing on here is that of Acme Archipelago, where biologists have been collecting demographic and genetic data from fishery samples for about 10 years. Ageing for this population has 100% accuracy (!) and is performed for juveniles by just counting milk-teeth, and for adults (after death) by sectioning the large tooth.

There are nrow(samp_delfi_A$Samps) (9691) invidivual samples (juveniles and adults) for which sex has been recorded (Sex, females only) and age estimated (A, from dental records).

nrow(samp_delfi_A$Samps)
[1] 9691

The sampling year in Samps is recorded in column Y and goes from Year min(samp_delfi_A$Samps$Y) (2015) to Year min(samp_delfi_A$Samps$Y) (2020).

The first column (Me) is a unique identifier for each individual consisting of four words—the first and fourth are unique to the individual and the second and third are the first component of the individual’s mother and father, respectively. So, you can use them to find (or verify) parent-offspring pairs.

NB: you’ll be reassured to know—I was—that Mark didn’t come up with an infinite list of weird syllabled words for the purpose of simulating pedigree—each word is called a proquint and is designed to be a pronounceable unique identifier, (see more here)[https://github.com/dsw/proquint].

Before we have a look at the samples, we’ll first create two columns poss_par and poss_off as booleans to identify each record as a potential “parent” or “offspring”. Since age-at-maturity is strictly 5, we can classify all individuals of age 4 or less as possible offsprings, and individuals of age 5 or more as possible parents.

samp_delfi_A$Samps$poss_off <- samp_delfi_A$Samps$A < agemat
samp_delfi_A$Samps$poss_par <- samp_delfi_A$Samps$A >= agemat

From there, we can look at the number of adults and offsprings that were sampled for each sampling year by adult age:

Data preparation

We first summarise the sampling data in order to generate the objects we need to compute the expected number of POPs in our dataset. Eventually, we will end up computing the probability, for each possible parent \(j\), that they are the parent of an offspring \(i\), given what we know about them (“the covariates”) (see “Modelling framework” below). For now, we start by exploring our samples in order to understand how the dataset gets broken down to generate quantities of interest for CKMR.

Let’s dig a bit into the probability of observing a POP. In order to be a possible parent to a given juvenile, you need, at the very least:

  • to have still been alive when the juvenile was born
  • to have been mature when the juvenile was born

The first item is given to us by the year of sampling. Since samples for Pinocchio’s dolphin come from dead bycaught individuals in the fishery, an adult cannot be the parent of a juvenile born in a year after it was sampled. The second item can be derived from the age of the adult at sampling, as that will give us the birth year, and, if we know age-at-maturity (as we do here), the year at which the adult started contributing to the offspring pool.

NB: For Pinocchio’s dolphin maturity is knife-edge at age 5, which simplifies things greatly. In most species, the switch to maturity would be spread over a few years.

The adult dataset can be re-arranged to better show the distribution of these key quantities (adult age, birth and maturity years) and how they are distributed in our dataset:

Code 
samp_delfi_A$Samps$B <- with(samp_delfi_A$Samps, Y - A) # add birth year B

# Aggregate samples by age / birth year / maturity year

So, most of the adults in our dataset became mature between years 2010 and 2015, and were sampled the year they became mature (because of fishing selectivity towards younger individuals). In the Acme Archipelago, the fishing season happens after the reproductive season, so the fished adults are still able to contribute to the offspring pool the year they are caught.

The key comparison for Pinocchio’s dolphin is whether an adult was mature and alive the year a juvenile was born. We can visualise this by directly juxtaposing the distribution of adult maturity and sampling years onto the distribution of juvenile birth years:

Base R:

Code 
offsprcnts <- with(samp_delfi_A$Samps[samp_delfi_A$Samps$poss_off,], table(B))
offsprcnts <- as.data.frame(offsprcnts, responseName = 'n')

At this stage, we have no other information that would allow us to differentiate the probability of adult \(i\) being the parent of offspring \(j\), other than the year of sampling, the age of the adult when sampled (which gives us the year when they were mature), and the birth date of the juveniles. Therefore, we can aggregate our adults according to those variables and make comparisons across the resulting strata, instead of making pairwise comparisons between each adult and juvenile samples. This is more efficient than looping through 2.281383^{7} pairwise comparisons (i.e. the number of adults \(\times\) the number of juveniles).

So, we want to compute the probability that a female of age \(A\) sampled in year \(Y\) is the mother of a juvenile of birth year \(B\), given the number of juveniles produced in year \(B\).

The exercise code fit_delfi_A.r implements this in two steps. First, prior to defining and fitting the models, quantities are computed by the function boring_data_prep_delfi_A which returns an environment object:

# use code from 'generic_lglk_MOP_ideal_mammal' to define likelihood
lglk_delfi_A <- generic_lglk_MOP_ideal_mammal 
env <- boring_data_prep_delfi_A(samp_delfi_A, prev_env=environment(lglk_delfi_A))

As the model itself is defined in lglk_delfi_A, we assign env as the environment of lglk_delfi_A, which makes the objects defined in env accessible to the code executed within lglk_delfi_A. The main advantage of doing this is that preliminary computations do not have to be provided as additional arguments to the lglk_delfi_A function, or redone from scratch for every model iteration. See here for a more in-depth explanation on how environments work in R.

One of two key quantities computed by boring_data_prep_delfi_A is the number of possible pairwise comparisons between adults and juveniles by \(Y\)-\(A\) \(\times\) \(B\) strata. Here, comparisons are only deemed possible if the adults in \(Y\)-\(A\) were born before the juveniles born in year \(B\). The number of possible comparisons is then the product of the number of adults in the \(Y\)-\(A\) stratum and the number of juveniles born in year \(B\) (i.e. \(B > Y - A\)).

Here’s an example (for one sampling year) of how to visualise the comparisons between the offsprings and their parents:

Code 
parentcntsmat <-  samp_delfi_A$Samps %>% filter(poss_par) %>%
    mutate(M=B+agemat) %>% group_by(Y, M) %>% tally() %>% mutate(lab='Maturity')

xl <- range(c(parentcntsmat$M, offsprcnts$B)) + c(-0.5, 0.5)

draw_comp_panel <- function(wsy=25, wcomp='All') { # which sampling year

    # get adults stats and counts for wsy
    oadf <- bind_rows(filter(parentcntsmat,  Y == wsy) %>%
                      mutate(Type = 'Adults', X = M),
                      mutate(offsprcnts, X = B, Type = 'Juveniles')) %>%
        mutate(Type=factor(Type, levels=c('Juveniles', 'Adults'), ordered=TRUE))

    # get plausible parent-offspring matches
    get_compdf <- function(wm) {
        ## to match boring_data_prep_delfi_A,
        ## only retain comparisons where adults were born >= juveniles birth year
        ## cf. n_comp_MOP_BYA
        oo <- offsprcnts %>%
            mutate(M=wm, Y=wsy) %>%
            # define types of pairwise comps
            mutate(All=TRUE,
                   Boring = B >= (M-5) & B <= Y,  # adults alive and born
                   Comp = B >= M & B <= Y) %>%  # adults alive and mature
            mutate(X=M) %>%
            filter((M-5) < B) %>% # filter out adults born after juveniles
            left_join(dplyr::select(filter(oadf, Type == 'Adults'), -B),
                      by=c('X', 'M', 'Y')) %>%
            mutate(Aad=Y-M+agemat)
    }

    compdf <- lapply(oadf$M, get_compdf) %>% bind_rows
    #    numc <- sum(with(filter(compdf, (Y - M - 5) < B), n.x * n.y), na.rm=TRUE)
    numc <- sum(with(filter(compdf, .data[[wcomp]]), n.x * n.y), na.rm=TRUE)    
    labs <- c('All'='Sampling year 2017\nAll possible pairwise comparisons where adults were *born*\nbefore juvenile birth year:',
              'Boring'='Only pairwise comparisons where adults were *born* before \nand still alive on juvenile birth year:',
              'Comp'='Only pairwise comparisons where adults were *mature*\nand still alive on juvenile birth year:')

    gg0 <- ggplot(oadf, aes(X, Type, fill=n)) +
        geom_tile(show.legend=FALSE) +
       scale_fill_gradientn(colours=rev(heat_hcl(40))) +
       geom_segment(data=filter(compdf, .data[[wcomp]]), aes(x=M, xend=B, y='Adults', yend='Juveniles', fill=NULL),
                    alpha=0.5, show.legend=FALSE, colour='royalblue3') +
       geom_text(aes(label=n), fontface=2, size=3) +
       annotate('text', x=Inf, y=Inf, label=paste('n =', numc), vjust=1.1, hjust=1) +
       xlab('') + ylab('') +
       xlim(xl) + ggtitle(labs[wcomp])

    gg0
}

lapply(c('All', 'Boring', 'Comp'), draw_comp_panel, wsy=2017) %>%
    wrap_plots(ncol=1) +
    xlab('\nAdult maturity year vs. juvenile birth year') +
    theme(axis.title.x=element_text(hjust=-2.25))

The lines show all possible comparisons that meet the stated requirement. The number in the top-right corner is the total possible number of pairwise comparisons in the sampling year.

The number of possible pairwise combinations is an important quantity as it scales the expected probability of observing a POP.

The number of pairwise comparisons by \(Y\)-\(A\) \(\times\) \(B\) strata are stored in object env$n_comp_MOP_BYA for instances where adults were born before the juvenile birth year (i.e. the top panel of the figure above). You can verify that the numbers match those in env$n_comp_MOP_BYA, and also examine individual counts by querying cells within the offarray object, e.g.:

[1] 3568533

will show the possible number of pairwise comparisons between juveniles born in 2011 and adults sampled in 2017 of age 19, and the total number of pairwise comparisons for adults sampled in 2017.

Note that objects of class offarray are indexed based on the name of the dimensions, not the cell positions. Use dimseq(env$n_comp_MOP_BYA) to view the name of the dimensions.

Modelling framework

Our end goal is to estimate population size per year, \(N_y\), for Pinocchio’s dolphin. We do this by maximising the likelihood of the observed parent-offspring-pairs given our population dynamics model and what we know about our samples (e.g., the year the juveniles were born in, the number of samples, etc.). As we are only including female samples, we are focusing on female population dynamics.

Let’s first define our population model.

For Pinocchio’s dolphin, reproductive output is independent of age, and of 1 offspring per year, such that population dynamics can be described as:

\[ N_t = N_0 e^\lambda \]

(Population numbers are low at the moment, so we can assume exponential growth).

Since the population abundance directly scales with the probability of observing an Parent-Offspring-Pair, we can work backwards from the estimated probability of \(Pr(POPs|N_0, \lambda)\) to gain an estimate of \(N_y\) (with a few assumptions…!).

The steps in the general CKMR modelling framework are:

  • Unpack model parameters
  • Predict population dynamics given parameters
  • Compute “true” expected probability of a POP
  • Compute actual expected probability of a POP given uncertainty about covariates
  • Return the likelihood of the observed number of POPs

(We can ignore step 4 since age is measured with 100% accuracy in the Acme Archipelago.)

These steps are implemented by the function generic_lglk_MOP_ideal_mammal which we’ve renamed lglk_delfi_A in this exercise. We go through each of these in the next section by examining key parts of the generic_lglk_MOP_ideal_mammal. The full code of generic_lglk_MOP_ideal_mammal is defined in ckmr_funs.r.

Model launch

The model is launched in fit_delfi_A.r by first defining the environment of lglk_delfi_A as env, which means that the quantities that were computed in the boring data prep step are accessible within the lglk_delfi_A local environment. We then fit the model in lglk_delfi_A with the function nlminb.

environment( lglk_delfi_A) <- env # include objects from preparation step to likelihood function environment

The full model is defined in generic_lglk_MOP_ideal_mammal in ckmr_funs.r, but we’ll go through the key steps below.

The first year of the model is the earliest birth year of juveniles sampled (e.g. “1993” if juveniles were born in 1993, 1994, and 1997—here, “2011”—see also env$Bju_range), the last year of the model is the last year an adult was sampled (here, “2020”). This range is also stored in model object env$years.

lglk_delfi_A follows the framework defined above. First, we start by back-transforming the two parameters of the population model, \(N_0\) and \(\lambda\):

## Unpack parameters
Nfad_y0 <- exp(params[1])
RoI <- params[2]

We then compute \(N_Y\) from years 2011 to 2020:

  N <- offarray( 0, first=min( years), last=max( years))
  N[] <- Nfad_y0 * exp( RoI * (years-y0))

Next, we compute the probability of a parent-offspring-pair given our covariates (offspring birth year, adult age at sampling and adult sampling year).

Since each Pinocchio’s dolphin female produces one offspring per year once mature, the number of recruits every year is the number of females in the population in year Y, so the probability that any recruit born in year \(B\) is the offspring of a possible parent female is \(\frac{1}{N_B}\).

The probability that a POP is detected in year Y for any females of age A and juveniles born in year B is thus:

  • the probability that a female of that age-year strata was still alive in year \(B\) [0/1] \(\times\)
  • the probability that a female of that age-year strata was mature in year \(B\) [0/1] \(\times\)
  • the inverse of the number of offspring produced in year B (\(\frac{1}{N_B}\)).

We thus loop through each combination of \(Y\)-\(A\) and \(B\) to compute this probability:

  # Ideal kinship probs, i.e. if know all important covariates perfectly
  Pr_MOP_BYA <- autoloop( Bju=Bju_range, Yad=Yad_range, Aad=Aad_range, {
    Bad <- Yad - Aad
    ( Bju <= Yad ) *          # was ad still alive at B[ju] ?
    ( Bju >= Amat + Bad ) *   # was ad mature at B[ju] ?
    ( 1/N[ Bju])              # ad's ERO at B[ju] if alive & mature, divided by TRO that year
  })

From this, we can predict the number of expected parent-offspring pairs detected given the sample size in each strata. The function lk_delfi_A outputs the (Poisson) likelihood of observing \(n_{Y, A, B}\) POPs given the expected \(n\) POPs for that stratum:

  lglk <- MAKE_FINITE( # anti-infinity guard
      sum( dpois( n_MOP_BYA, lambda=n_comp_MOP_BYA * Pr_MOP_BYA, log=TRUE))
    )

The model is then optimised (with nlminb) to find the combination of \(N_0\) and \(\lambda\) that minimises that log-likelihood.

# test some starting values for logNad and RoI 
starto <- c( log( 100000), 0.01) 
initest <- lglk_delfi_A( starto)

# fit model:
fitto <- nlminb( starto, NEG( lglk_delfi_A))

The values of \(N_0\) and \(\lambda\) that optimise the likelihood are 1.02782^{4} and 0.0121. Let’s compare that to the true values that were used when simulating the dataset:

Nfad_y0 <- exp(fitto$par[1])
RoI <- fitto$par[2]
N_y <- Nfad_y0 * exp( RoI * (env$years - env$y0))

# get true value for female population 'F': 
tru_Nadf <- apply(samp_delfi_A@secret$N_sya['F', env$years, agemat:40], 2, sum) 

maxyplot <- max( c( tru_Nadf, N_y))
par(mai=c(1, 1, 0.5, 0))
plot( env$years, tru_Nadf, type='l', ylim=c( 0, 1.1*maxyplot),
     xlab = 'Year', ylab='Numbers\n', las=1, yaxs='i')
points( env$years, env$N, col='turquoise4', pch=16)

Not bad! There are more diagnostics and options for exploring results in fit_delphi_A.r.

Diagnostics

Diagnostics for CKMR can be tricky as there is often a very small amount of observed POPs.

This example actually contains a huge amount of POPs compared to what we would usually observe, so we can compare observed vs. expected POPs for each sampling year and juvenile birth year.

The expected POPs are:

round(sumover(with(env, n_comp_MOP_BYA * Pr_MOP_BYA), c('Bju', 'Aad')), 1)
Yad
[2015] [2016] [2017] [2018] [2019] [2020] 
 136.8  138.1  121.8   85.3   46.6   31.4

and the observed POPs are:

sumover(env$n_MOP_BYA, c('Bju', 'Aad'))
Yad
[2015] [2016] [2017] [2018] [2019] [2020] 
   157    128    114     90     36     35

If we plot them we can see that prediction appears unbiased with no trend over time.

Code 
diagdf <- data.frame(sumover(with(env, n_comp_MOP_BYA * Pr_MOP_BYA),
                             c('Bju', 'Aad')),
                     sumover(env$n_MOP_BYA, c('Bju', 'Aad'))) %>%
    dplyr::select(Yad, Expected=response, Observed=response.1) %>%
    gather(Type, Number, Expected:Observed)

ggplot(diagdf, aes(Yad, Number, fill=Type)) +
    geom_bar(stat='identity', position=position_dodge()) +
    scale_fill_manual(values=c('honeydew3', 'cadetblue3')) +
    xlab('\nYear of sampling') + ylab('Count\n') +
    theme(legend.position=c(0.8, 0.9))

Base R:

Code 
tmp <- data.frame(sumover(with(env, n_comp_MOP_BYA * Pr_MOP_BYA),
                             c('Bju', 'Aad')),
                     sumover(env$n_MOP_BYA, c('Bju', 'Aad')))
tmp <- tmp[, c('Yad', 'response', 'response.1')]

diagdf <- rbind(data.frame(Yad=tmp$Yad,
                           Number=tmp$response,
                           Type='Expected'),
                data.frame(Yad=tmp$Yad,
                           Number=tmp$response.1,
                           Type='Observed'))

(NB: If we wanted to do this properly we could do a \(\chi^2\)-test.

For a normal dataset with less POPs, we would aggregate time-periods instead of inspecting individual years (e.g. first half vs. second half time-series).
